This happens when you initiate an object with `new` and try to print or do anything with it. Below is the example that throws the stack overflow error:
    
    JSONObject outerMostObj = new JSONObject();
    outerMostObj.put(&quot;authFailure&quot;, outerMostObj);
    System.out.println(&quot;Rretrun vaklueeee&quot; + outerMostObj);
    
To resolve -&gt; You need to assign proper value for the object and print or do whatever you want. Simple! :)

    JSONObject outerMostObj = new JSONObject();
    JSONObject outerMostObj = fetch.getJSONValue(); //added this one
    outerMostObj.put(&quot;authFailure&quot;, outerMostObj);
    System.out.println(&quot;Rretrun vaklueeee&quot; + outerMostObj);

# You could...

Reset the `TableModel`&#39;s content.  When using `DefaultTableModel`, you can simply set the row count to `0`

    DefaultTableModel model = (DefaultTableModel)table.getModel();
    model.setRowCount(0);

# You could...

Build a new `TableModel` from scratch.  This is probably a safer option, as it doesn&#39;t rely on you known what type of `TableModel` the `JTable` is currently using.

     DefaultTableModel model = new DefaultTableModel();
    Object[] tableLines = br.lines().toArray();
    
    for (Object tableLine : tableLines) {
        String line = tableLine.toString().trim();
        String[] dataRow = line.split(&quot;,&quot;);
        model.addRow(dataRow);
        //System.out.print(Arrays.toString(dataRow));
    }
    table.setModel(model);

It will probably also be faster as the model isn&#39;t causing the table to trigger new updates each time you add a new row

